profile  command


The `.. /profile` command is used to access the profile file of the current user in Linux. The profile file is a script that runs when the shell starts and can be used to customize the environment. For example, you can add aliases, functions, variables, modules, drives, commands, and preference settings to your profile file¹².

To view the profile file, you can use the `cat` command:

`cat .. /profile`

To edit the profile file, you can use your preferred editor, such as `vi` or `gedit`:

`vi .. /profile`

`gedit .. /profile`

Note: To quit `vi`, type `:q` and press `Enter`². To quit `less`, press `q`².

¹: Customizing your shell environment - PowerShell | Microsoft Learn
²: files - How to view profile on Linux - Ask Ubuntu

